# modeling using KNN algo 
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
k_range = range(1, 26)
scores = {}
score_list=[]
for k in k_range:
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    knn.fit(X_train, Y_train)
    prediction = knn.predict(X_test)
    scores[k] = metrics.accuracy_score(Y_test, prediction)
    score_list.append(scores[k])
    
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
print(score_list)
plt.plot(k_range, score_list)

# The Logistics regression algo and KNN algos both produce results with similar accuracy but LRC 
print("Since we are interested in the positive outcome where we target the most probable customers to become a")
print(" personal loan customer, we need to look at the precision with more wightage.")
print("KNN precision - 0.9491884262526464")
print("LRC precision - 0.9556191839656407")
print("\nAs we could see that LRC performs better than the best KNN model we can prefer to use Logistics Regression for the problem at hand!")
